  1. The functions spread() and gather() are not perfectly symmetrical because the type of variables might change after this process. When variables are gathered, they are always converted into chr. In this example, the type of variable year is transformed from dbl to chr.

  2. This code fails because 1999 and 2000 are treated as numbers, which makes them not able to be recognized as the column names. To fix it, we need to put them in `` to convert them into characters.

#error
table4a %>% gather(1999, 2000, key = "year", value = "cases") 
#modification
table4a %>% gather(`1999`, `2000`, key = "year", value = "cases")

  1. The argument extra in separate() controls what happens when there are too many pieces. It contains three valid options: (1)warn (the default): emit a warning and drop extra values. (2)drop: drop any extra values without a warning. (3)merge: only splits at most length(into) times.
    The argument fill in separate() controls what happens when there are not enough pieces. It contains three valid options: (1)warn (the default): emit a warning and fill from the right. (2)right: fill with missing values on the right. (3)left: fill with missing values on the left.
#original tibble
tibble(x = c("a,b,c", "d,e,f,g", "h,i,j")) %>% 
  separate(x, c("one", "two", "three"))

# tidy the dataset 
who <- tidyr::who
who_tidy <- 
  who %>%
  gather(key, value, new_sp_m014:newrel_f65) %>% 
  mutate(key = stringr::str_replace(key, "newrel", "new_rel")) %>%
  separate(key, c("new", "var", "sexage")) %>% 
  select(-new) %>% 
  separate(sexage, c("sex", "age"), sep = 1)

2.1 Merge Provider Costs with Provider Case-Mix

  1. inner_join() command returns all rows from x where there are matching values in y, and all columns from x and y. If there are multiple matches between x and y, all combination of the matches are returned. The required arguments are x and y, which are the tibbles to join.

  2. str_sub will recycle all arguments to be the same length as the longest argument. If any arguments are of length 0, the output will be a zero length character vector. The required argument are string, start and end.
    str_trim() removes whitespace from start and end of string.

  3. The ve types of information that are available in both datasets include : episode, therapy visits, clinical severity level, functional severity level and service severity level. Episode describes during which episode a patient visits the agency. Therapy visits describe the number of visits in an episode. Clinical, functional and service severity level all describes how severe the disease of a patient is.

2.2 Billing Outlier Analysis

#Construct provider_sum
provider_sum <-
  provider_hhrg_wt %>%
  group_by(`Provider ID`) %>%
  summarise(`Agency Name` = unique(`Agency Name`),
            State = unique(State),
            mean_pay_wt_ep = weighted.mean(`Average HHA Medicare Payment Amount`, `Total Episodes`),
            mean_pay_wt_ca = weighted.mean(`Average HHA Medicare Payment Amount`, weights_2014),
            c_mix_wtmean = weighted.mean(weights_2014, `Total Episodes`),
            n_total_epi = sum(`Total Episodes`))
  1. The average cost varies more in higher range and there are only outliers of high cost and no outliers of low cost.
ggplot(provider_sum, aes(y = mean_pay_wt_ep)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  ylab(" average cost per episode by home-health agency")

  1. The outliers of average cost after accounting for case-mix weight locate more densely.
ggplot(provider_sum, aes(y = mean_pay_wt_ca)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  ylab("average cost adjusted by case-mix weight")

  1. The red histogram is average cost per episode across HHAs and the blue histogram is the normalized average cost adjusted by case-mix. We can see that the dispersion of cost has been reduced after normalization.
provider_sum <-
  provider_sum %>%
  mutate(cost_normalized = mean_pay_wt_ep / c_mix_wtmean)

ggplot(data = provider_sum) + 
    geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = mean_pay_wt_ep), fill = "red", alpha = 0.5) + 
    geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = cost_normalized), fill = "blue", alpha = 0.5)  
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

  1. The top 5 HHAs with the highest billing per episode in Illinois are: PRIME CARE RESOURCE, INC, FORUM HEALTH CARE, SIMPLY HOME HEALTH, LLC, HOME BOUND HEALTHCARE, INC and WHITESTAR HOME HEALTH INC.
    The top 5 HHAs with the highest markups are : FAIRFIELD MEMORIAL HOSPITAL, HENDERSON COUNTY HEALTH DEPART, BEST CARE HOME HEALTH, INC., QUANTUM HEALTHCARE SERVICES, INC and SWEDISH COVENANT HOSPITAL HOME. There isnt any overlapping in these two lists.
top5_unadj <- 
  provider_sum %>%
  filter(State == "IL") %>%
  arrange(desc(mean_pay_wt_ep)) %>% 
  slice(1:5) 

ggplot(top5_unadj, aes(x = reorder(`Agency Name`, mean_pay_wt_ep), y = mean_pay_wt_ep)) + 
  geom_col() + 
  ylab("unadjusted average cost") +
  coord_flip()

top5_norm <-
  provider_sum %>%
  filter(State == "IL") %>%
  arrange(desc(cost_normalized)) %>% 
  slice(1:5)

ggplot(top5_norm, aes(x = reorder(`Agency Name`, cost_normalized), y = cost_normalized)) + 
  geom_col() + 
  ylab("normalized average cost") +
  coord_flip()
